				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/stormbreath" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(3075960); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=3075960&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610252374" alt="stormbreath" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=3075960)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/stormbreath" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(3075960); return false;" >stormbreath</a></span> <span class="odate time_1584648123 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">19 Mar 2020 20:02</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4555723">
									

<p>Alright, I promised I'd review this and explain my downvote.</p>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;Review</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">-1</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p>So the first thing first is that you've absolutely mucked up your @imports. Like, this is an absolute disaster. To note:</p>
<ul>
<li>In the &quot;theme code&quot; collapsible section, you start by trying (unsucccesfully) @importing a file document into itself. The url is wrong here, preventing it from breaking anything (There's a missing backslash between &quot;laruetheme&quot; and &quot;code&quot;. It'd also be better practice to use the actual url you are redirected to when punching the url you are trying to use in, rather than this: it speeds up the code and makes it easier.</li>
<li>You @import the fonts into the page specific CSS module at the start, the one that only applies to the theme page.</li>
<li>All of your font imports are missing from the theme itself. You instead have them in your second CSS module at the end, which should really only be used to @import the theme itself. I was absolutely baffled for a minute trying to figure out where your fonts were coming from. You need to replace the broken @import at the start of the theme code with the font imports.</li>
</ul>
<p>In the :root, it'd probably be best to remove all the comments associated with each variable. Those are in the Black Highlighter theme for people making new themes to know what to do: they aren't serving any purpose <em>here</em>, just clogging the theme up.</p>
<p>Reading through a CSS root is always a dense process, and I admit that I skimmed this part, but I found a few variables that are unchanged from Black Highlighter. These are therefore, by definition, bloat code, and should be removed.</p>
<p>The spacing on the lines here is generally pretty off. It looks like you've got about four extra/unnecessary spaces before each line. While this doesn't affect the theme's function, it does hurt readability for somebody trying to figure out what it does (like me). I'd brush up on how <a href="https://css-tricks.com/different-ways-to-format-css/">CSS formatting</a> is supposed to look (Multi-Line with Indenting is the general standard on the site, with the indenting being used for code contained within an @media or @supports query).</p>
<p>Your <tt>side-bar a</tt> and <tt>side-bar a:visited</tt> colors are different. There isn't much to say about this other than that it's a bad aesthetic choice. What side-bar links a user has visited is always random dependent on the user, and frequently without much rhyme/reason (I, for instance, have visited the Series I and Series VI pages, but none of the other four, nor their equivalent Tales by Series pages. This means it's basically random which links are colored different for me.)</p>
<div class="code">
<pre>
<code>   blockquote {
   display: inline-block;
   color:   rgb(var(--light-pale-gray-monochrome));
   border-radius: 10px; 
   border:dashed 1px rgb(var(--black-monochrome-alt));  
   background: rgb(var(--dark-gray-monochrome)); 
   float:top; 
   padding:10px;
    }</code>
</pre></div>
<p>I can count at least 4 problems in these lines. The first is the formatting, which is all over the place: you've got three spaces after <tt>color:</tt>, zero after <tt>float:, padding: and border</tt> and 1 after everywhere else. None is wrong, but you have to be consistent. You also close the code with a bracket that's indented so far it's <span style="text-decoration: underline;">under</span> the arguments.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>display: inline-block</p>
</blockquote>
<p>This is unnecessary and wrong. This is an argument that somehow slipped into a div on this site years ago and has been mindlessly copied since by dozens of users, always managing to mess things up. This isn't on you, per se, but this line breaks stuff. Look at your example block quotes on this page. See how they're weirdly small? This line is why.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>float:top;</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Not a property that exists in CSS, and if it wasn't, you wouldn't want it.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>padding:10px;</p>
</blockquote>
<p>This is the least dramatic of the problems, but it's <em>weird</em>. See, BHL already defines padding for blockquotes at <tt>0&#160;1em</tt>, so this adds 10 pixels in one dimension and removes 2 in the other. There isn't really any clear reason to have it. If it ain't broken, don't fix it. This isn't doing anything relevant to the aesthetics of this theme, and it's just sorta &#8230; there.</p>
<p>The final issue with blockquotes is that it'd be idea to define them like so:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>blockquote,<br />
.blockquote {</p>
</blockquote>
<p>This would allow for compatibility between this theme and the <tt>[[div class=&quot;blockquote&quot;]]</tt> feature of BHL.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>

